Part I - PISA Data Exploration¶

by Abdessalam Dai¶

Introduction¶

PISA is a survey of students' skills and knowledge as they approach the end of compulsory education. It is not a conventional school test. Rather than examining how well students have learned the school curriculum, it looks at how well prepared they are for life beyond school.

Around 510,000 students in 65 economies took part in the PISA 2012 assessment of reading, mathematics and science representing about 28 million 15-year-olds globally. Of those economies, 44 took part in an assessment of creative problem solving and 18 in an assessment of financial literacy.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 485,490 students in the dataset with 635 features but we loaded only 10 features (country. gender, mother_at_home, father_at_home, parents_education_level, computer_use_time, wealth, math_avg, reading_avg and science_avg). After cleaning the dataset we're left with 268,414 students.

The variables country, gender, mother_at_home, father_at_home and parents_education_level are categorical and other variables are numeric.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

We are interested in answering the following questions:

  • What are the effects of gender on students' scores on different subjects?
  • Which countries have better scores in different subjects?
  • Does parental companionship influence student's scores?
  • Are there relationships between math score, reading score and science score?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that females will perform better than males in all subjects. Additionally, I expect that Asian students will perform better in math and science subjects.

Univariate Exploration¶

Let's create this function that makes count plots, we're going to use it in several explorations later.

In [14]:
def count_plot(df, x_var, hue_var=None, color=0, palette=None, order=None, hue_order=None, figsize=(14, 6), orient='v'):
    # this function plots a count plot
    
    # figsize must be turned off for subplots
    if figsize:
        plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    
    if orient=='v': # vertical orientation
        kwargs = {'x': x_var, 'color': None if color == 'all' else sns.color_palette()[color]}
    elif orient=='h': # horizontal orientation
        kwargs = {'y': x_var, 'color': None if color == 'all' else sns.color_palette()[color]}
    else:
        print('Orient has to be either "h" or "v"')
        
    # make the plot
    ax = sns.countplot(data=df, hue=hue_var, palette=palette,
                       order=order, hue_order=hue_order,
                       **kwargs)
    
    # clean up variable names
    x_var = x_var.replace('_', ' ').title()
    if hue_var:
        hue_var = hue_var.replace('_', ' ').title()
    
    # set title
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {x_var} {"by" if hue_var else ""} {hue_var if hue_var else ""}',
              size=20, weight='bold');
    # dictionnary for the labels keywords
    keys = {f'{"y" if orient=="h" else "x"}label':x_var, f'{"y" if orient=="v" else "x"}label': 'Count'}
    plt.gca().set(**keys)

Average Scores Based on Gender¶

Male students outperform female students in math while female students outperform male students in reading. In terms of average science scores, both genders are almost equal.

In [24]:

Scores Distrubtion Based on Gender¶

Males consistently perform better than females in math. But when it comes to reading, it's the opposite.

In [25]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize = (15, 4))

binsize = 10

subjects_scores = {'Math Score': 'math_avg', 'Reading Score': 'reading_avg', 'Science Score': 'science_avg'}
for idx, sub in enumerate(subjects_scores):
    bin_edges = np.arange(df[subjects_scores[sub]].min(), df[subjects_scores[sub]].max()+binsize, binsize)
    ax = fig.add_subplot(1,3,idx+1)
    plt.hist(data=df.query('gender == "Female"'), x=subjects_scores[sub], alpha=.4, bins=bin_edges, label='Female')
    plt.hist(data=df.query('gender == "Male"'), x=subjects_scores[sub], alpha=.4, bins=bin_edges, label='Male')
    plt.legend();
    ax.set(xlabel=sub, ylabel='Number of Students')
    plt.title(f'{sub}', size=20);

Multivariate Exploration¶

Parental Companionship in Math, Reading and Science¶

Let us first calculate the number of parents at home for each student and then do the following transformation:

0 = None

1 = One

2 = Both

In [28]:
df['father_at_home'] = df['father_at_home'].replace({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})
df['mother_at_home'] = df['mother_at_home'].replace({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})

df['parents_at_home'] = df['father_at_home'] + df['mother_at_home']
df['parents_at_home'] = df['parents_at_home'].replace({0: 'None', 1: 'One', 2: 'Both'})

The figure below is solid evidence for this; if at least one parent is home, the child scores higher than a child whose parents are not home.

Average Score in Different Countries for Each Subject¶

Here, we can see how different scores are distributed among the various countries.

  • East Asian countries have higher average math test scores include China, Korea, Singapore, and Hong Kong.
  • Science: Singapore, Finland and Australia are more significant
  • Reading: Successful countries included Spain, Singapore, New Zealand, China, and Japan.

Conclusions¶

  • Parents presence at home will influence their children's performances.
  • Girls' reading abilities are superior to boys'.
  • Science and math scores for girls are on par with those for boys.
  • There is a strong positive correlation between each subject and the other.
  • Asian countries appear to have slightly higher scores.
